The section below is ran to determine the Avarage Well Colour Development (AWCD) of each Ecoplate. AWCD needs to be determined as a prerequisite for further analysis. Therefore this section will be ran twice: Once without the EcoPlate standardisation and transformation to determine AWCD, and once with standardisation and transformation, afterwich analysis will commence.

Standardisation & Transformation was performed as described by Garland,s Biolog standardization (Garland 1997) 1. calculate the mean of the plate blanks (water) 2. subtract blanks mean from each wells Optical Density (OD) reading 3. if the total OD is less than 0, then replace it with 0 4. divide each OD reading with the AWCD, excluding blanks 5. Each sample is repeated three time in and EcoPlate, and therefore, the mean of the normalized absorbency for the three replicates on each microplate was used. AWCD must be determined for each plate as part of the incubation time point selection criteria. The below function must be ran: excluding the EcoPlate_rezult <- EcoPlate_rezult/mean(EcoPlate_rezult) and EcoPlate_rezult <- log2(EcoPlate_rezult+1) Once the AWCD has been determined the function must be ran, including the EcoPlate_rezult <- EcoPlate_rezult/mean(EcoPlate_rezult) and EcoPlate_rezult <- log2(EcoPlate_rezult+1) before the analysis can continue.

EcoPlate_standards <- function(data){#Substrate mean-blank mean and <0=0
  EcoPlate_rezult <- rowMeans(data.frame(bind_cols(as.data.frame(
    ifelse(data.frame(s1=c(data$V1,data$V2,data$V3,data$V4))
           -mean(c(data$V1[1],data$V5[1],data$V9[1]))<0,0,
           (s1=c(data$V1,data$V2,data$V3,data$V4))
           -mean(c(data$V1[1],data$V5[1],data$V9[1])))),
    ifelse(data.frame(s2=c(data$V5,data$V6,data$V7,data$V8))
           -mean(c(data$V1[1],data$V5[1],data$V9[1]))<0,0,
           (s2=c(data$V5,data$V6,data$V7,data$V8))
           -mean(c(data$V1[1],data$V5[1],data$V9[1]))),
    ifelse(data.frame(s3=c(data$V9,data$V10,data$V11,data$V12))
           -mean(c(data$V1[1],data$V5[1],data$V9[1]))<0,0,
           (s3=c(data$V9,data$V10,data$V11,data$V12))
           -mean(c(data$V1[1],data$V5[1],data$V9[1]))))))[-1]
  EcoPlate_rezult <- EcoPlate_rezult # Just the means
#    EcoPlate_rezult <- EcoPlate_rezult/mean(EcoPlate_rezult) #REMOVE FOR AWCD
#   EcoPlate_rezult <- log2(EcoPlate_rezult+1)#REMOVE FOR AWCD
  return(EcoPlate_rezult)
}
EcoPlate_grouped <- function(samples){
  Grouped_samples <- samples%>%
    t()%>%
    `colnames<-`(as.character(c("Pyruvic Acid Methyl Ester","Tween 40", "Tween 80","-Cyclodextrin","Glycogen","D-Cellobiose", "-D-Lactose", "-Methyl-D-Glucoside", "D-Xylose","i-Erythritol","D-Mannitol", "N-Acetyl-D-Glucosamine","D-Glucosaminic Acid","Glucose-1-Phosphate","D,L--Glycerol Phosphate","D-Galactonic Acid -Lactone", "D-Galacturonic Acid","2-Hydroxy Benzoic Acid", "4-Hydroxy Benzoic Acid", "-Amino Butyric Acid","Itaconic Acid", "-Keto Butyric Acid","D-Malic Acid","L-Arginine", "L-Asparagine", "L-Phenylalanine", "L-Serine", "L-Threonine", "Glycyl-L-Glutamic Acid","Phenylethylamine", "Putrescine")))%>%
    
    cbind.data.frame(Site,Group)%>%
    relocate(Site,.before = "Pyruvic Acid Methyl Ester")%>%
    relocate(Group,.after = Site)%>%
    as.data.frame()
  
  return(Grouped_samples)
}

EcoPlate_standards function.

##Matrix for 31 carbon substrates####
To_matrix <- function(data){
  Results_t <-as.data.frame(paste(Site, data$Group))# combine the group and site variables
  Results_tt <- bind_cols(as.data.frame(Results_t), data) # create a new unique variable name
  colnames(Results_tt)[colnames(Results_tt)=="paste(Site, Results_t$Group)"] <- "SitePlace" #give the new variable a name
  Results_T <- Results_tt[-2:-3]# remove the group and site variables
  write.csv(Results_T, file = "TM_Results.csv", row.names = FALSE)# create a csv file 
  TMResults <- read.csv("TM_Results.csv", TRUE, sep = ",", row.names = 1, check.names = F)
  TM1H72 <- as.matrix(TMResults) # change the csv file to a data matrix
  return(TM1H72)
}
###H72####
TM1H72 <- To_matrix(M1H72)
TM6H72 <- To_matrix(M6H72)
TM12H72 <- To_matrix(M12H72)
TM18H72 <- To_matrix(M18H72)
###H144####
TM1H144 <- To_matrix(M1H144)
TM6H144 <- To_matrix(M6H144)
TM12H144 <- To_matrix(M12H144)
TM18H144 <- To_matrix(M18H144)
###H216####
TM1H216 <- To_matrix(M1H216)
TM6H216 <- To_matrix(M6H216)
TM12H216 <- To_matrix(M12H216)
TM18H216 <- To_matrix(M18H216)

The EcoPlate AWCD were compared at 0, 72, 144 and 216 hours of incubation to determine a suitable incubation time point for further statistical comparisons. The AWCD means were also compared with t-tests although many of the samples were not normally distributed and heteroscedasticity was observed. In addition, as
there were only 10 replicates (>15 being ideal) non-parametric statistical testing was performed (Wilcoxon test).

##M1####
###M1H0####
AWCD_M1H0_Bnth <- c( mean(M1H0_S1_0M),mean(M1H0_S3_0M),mean(M1H0_S4_0M),
                     mean(M1H0_S6_0M),mean(M1H0_S8_0M),mean(M1H0_S9_0M),
                     mean(M1H0_S11_0M),mean(M1H0_S12_0M),mean(M1H0_S13_0M),
                     mean(M1H0_S15_0M))
shapiro.test(AWCD_M1H0_Bnth)
AWCD_M1H0_Ctrl <- c( mean(M1H0_S1_5M),mean(M1H0_S3_5M),mean(M1H0_S4_5M),
                     mean(M1H0_S6_5M),mean(M1H0_S8_5M),mean(M1H0_S9_5M),
                     mean(M1H0_S11_5M),mean(M1H0_S12_5M),mean(M1H0_S13_5M),
                     mean(M1H0_S15_5M))
shapiro.test(AWCD_M1H0_Ctrl)
SD_M1H0_Bnth <- c( sd(M1H0_S1_0M),sd(M1H0_S3_0M),sd(M1H0_S4_0M),
                   sd(M1H0_S6_0M),sd(M1H0_S8_0M),sd(M1H0_S9_0M),
                   sd(M1H0_S11_0M),sd(M1H0_S12_0M),sd(M1H0_S13_0M),
                   sd(M1H0_S15_0M))
SD_M1H0_Ctrl <- c( sd(M1H0_S1_5M),sd(M1H0_S3_5M),sd(M1H0_S4_5M),
                   sd(M1H0_S6_5M),sd(M1H0_S8_5M),sd(M1H0_S9_5M),
                   sd(M1H0_S11_5M),sd(M1H0_S12_5M),sd(M1H0_S13_5M),
                   sd(M1H0_S15_5M))

H0 <- as.numeric('0')
SD_M1H0 <- bind_cols(SD_M1H0_Bnth,SD_M1H0_Ctrl,H0)
colnames(SD_M1H0) <- c("beneath","control",'incubation')
SD_M1H0 <- pivot_longer(data = SD_M1H0, names_to = "treatment",values_to = "Standard deviation",
                        cols = c("beneath","control"))
SD_M1H0 <- arrange(SD_M1H0,treatment)

H0 <- as.numeric('0')
AWCD_M1H0 <- bind_cols(AWCD_M1H0_Bnth,AWCD_M1H0_Ctrl,H0)
colnames(AWCD_M1H0) <- c("beneath","control",'incubation')
AWCD_M1H0 <- pivot_longer(data = AWCD_M1H0, names_to = "treatment",values_to = "AWCD",
                          cols = c("beneath","control"))
AWCD_M1H0 <- arrange(AWCD_M1H0,treatment)

                       mean(M1H72_S11_5M),mean(M1H72_S12_5M),mean(M1H72_S13_5M),
                       mean(M1H72_S15_5M))
shapiro.test(AWCD_M1H0_Ctrl)
SD_M1H72_Bnth <- c( sd(M1H72_S1_0M),sd(M1H72_S3_0M),sd(M1H72_S4_0M),
                     sd(M1H72_S6_0M),sd(M1H72_S8_0M),sd(M1H72_S9_0M),

                            cols = c("beneath","control"))

leveneTest(AWCD~treatment, data = AWCD_M1H72)
t.test(AWCD~treatment, data = AWCD_M1H72,var.equal=T)
wilcox.test(AWCD~treatment, data = AWCD_M1H72,paired=T)

AWCD growth (OD) curves were created to assess the development phases. The curves were smoothed to clearly indicate the phases.

binomial_smooth <-  function(...) {
  geom_smooth(method = "glm", method.args = list(family = "binomial"), ...)
}

##AWCD_M1_Plot####
AWCD_M1 <- 
  ggplot(M1AWCD, aes(incubation,AWCD,fill = treatment,colour = treatment))+
  #  geom_jitter(show.legend = F, shape=1, height = 0, width = 40)+
  binomial_smooth(formula = y ~ splines::ns(x, 2), se=F,show.legend = F)+
  scale_colour_manual(values = c("red4","darkolivegreen"))+
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("red4","darkolivegreen"))+
  xlim(-0.8,216)+
  ylim(0,1)+
  theme+
  theme(plot.title=element_text(hjust=0.5))+
  labs(x = NULL, y = NULL,title = 'One month')

  scale_colour_manual(values = c("red4","darkolivegreen"))+
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("red4","darkolivegreen"))+
  xlim(0,216)+
  ylim(0,.5)+

In conjunction with the growth phase results the time-point selection criteria included: The number of responses(>0.25), values above 2 and standard deviation (Weber & Legge 2010).

#-end of AWCD section#####

One hundred forty-four incubation hours was selected as the most appropriate time point for comparison. In section below the: EcoPlate_rezult <- EcoPlate_rezult/mean(EcoPlate_rezult) #REMOVED FOR AWCD and EcoPlate_rezult <- log2(EcoPlate_rezult+1) are replaced in the function.

EcoPlate_standards <- function(data){#Substrate mean-blank mean and <0=0
  EcoPlate_rezult <- rowMeans(data.frame(bind_cols(as.data.frame(
    ifelse(data.frame(s1=c(data$V1,data$V2,data$V3,data$V4))
           -mean(c(data$V1[1],data$V5[1],data$V9[1]))<0,0,
           (s1=c(data$V1,data$V2,data$V3,data$V4))
           -mean(c(data$V1[1],data$V5[1],data$V9[1])))),
    ifelse(data.frame(s2=c(data$V5,data$V6,data$V7,data$V8))
           -mean(c(data$V1[1],data$V5[1],data$V9[1]))<0,0,
           (s2=c(data$V5,data$V6,data$V7,data$V8))
           -mean(c(data$V1[1],data$V5[1],data$V9[1]))),
    ifelse(data.frame(s3=c(data$V9,data$V10,data$V11,data$V12))
           -mean(c(data$V1[1],data$V5[1],data$V9[1]))<0,0,
           (s3=c(data$V9,data$V10,data$V11,data$V12))
           -mean(c(data$V1[1],data$V5[1],data$V9[1]))))))[-1]
  EcoPlate_rezult <- EcoPlate_rezult # Just the means
    EcoPlate_rezult <- EcoPlate_rezult/mean(EcoPlate_rezult) #REMOVE FOR AWCD
   EcoPlate_rezult <- log2(EcoPlate_rezult+1)#REMOVE FOR AWCD
  return(EcoPlate_rezult)
}
EcoPlate_grouped <- function(samples){
  Grouped_samples <- samples%>%
    t()%>%
    `colnames<-`(as.character(c("Pyruvic Acid Methyl Ester","Tween 40", "Tween 80","-Cyclodextrin","Glycogen","D-Cellobiose", "-D-Lactose",  "-Methyl-D-Glucoside", "D-Xylose","i-Erythritol","D-Mannitol", "N-Acetyl-D-Glucosamine","D-Glucosaminic Acid","Glucose-1-Phosphate","D,L--Glycerol Phosphate","D-Galactonic Acid -Lactone", "D-Galacturonic Acid","2-Hydroxy Benzoic Acid", "4-Hydroxy Benzoic Acid", "-Amino Butyric Acid","Itaconic Acid", "-Keto Butyric Acid","D-Malic Acid","L-Arginine", "L-Asparagine", "L-Phenylalanine", "L-Serine", "L-Threonine", "Glycyl-L-Glutamic Acid","Phenylethylamine", "Putrescine")))%>%
    
    cbind.data.frame(Site,Group)%>%
    relocate(Site,.before = "Pyruvic Acid Methyl Ester")%>%
    relocate(Group,.after = Site)%>%
    as.data.frame()
  
  return(Grouped_samples)
}

The data is again imported but this time it isStandardised and transformed b the function. (Created files are rewritten and replaced)

##Matrix for 31 carbon substrates####
To_matrix <- function(data){
  Results_t <-as.data.frame(paste(Site, data$Group))# combine the group and site variables
  Results_tt <- bind_cols(as.data.frame(Results_t), data) # create a new unique variable name
  colnames(Results_tt)[colnames(Results_tt)=="paste(Site, Results_t$Group)"] <- "SitePlace" #give the new variable a name
  Results_T <- Results_tt[-2:-3]# remove the group and site variables
  write.csv(Results_T, file = "TM_Results.csv", row.names = FALSE)# create a csv file 
  TMResults <- read.csv("TM_Results.csv", TRUE, sep = ",", row.names = 1, check.names = F)
  TM1H72 <- as.matrix(TMResults) # change the csv file to a data matrix
  return(TM1H72)
}
###H72####
TM1H72 <- To_matrix(M1H72)
TM6H72 <- To_matrix(M6H72)
TM12H72 <- To_matrix(M12H72)
TM18H72 <- To_matrix(M18H72)
###H144####
TM1H144 <- To_matrix(M1H144)
TM6H144 <- To_matrix(M6H144)
TM12H144 <- To_matrix(M12H144)
TM18H144 <- To_matrix(M18H144)
###H216####
TM1H216 <- To_matrix(M1H216)

TM12H216 <- To_matrix(M12H216)

Substrate guild utilisation The standardised and transformed data were grouped into 6 substrate guilds (Rutgers et al., 2016; Preston-Mafham et al., 2002; etc.)

Guilds6 <- function(data){# Structure in six chemical guilds
  GLDS <- M1H72 %>% 
    transmute("Amines" =
                rowMeans(cbind(data$Phenylethylamine, 
                               data$Putrescine),
                         na.rm = T)) %>%
    mutate("Carboxylic Acids" = 
             rowMeans(cbind(data$`D-Galacturonic Acid`,
                            data$`Pyruvic Acid Methyl Ester`,
                            data$`-Amino Butyric Acid`,
                            data$`Itaconic Acid`,
                            data$`-Keto Butyric Acid`,
                            data$`D-Malic Acid`),
                      na.rm = T)) %>%
    
    mutate("Amino Acids" = 
             rowMeans(cbind(data$`L-Arginine`,
                            data$`L-Asparagine`,
                            data$`L-Phenylalanine`,
                            data$`L-Serine`,
                            data$`L-Threonine`,
                            data$`Glycyl-L-Glutamic Acid`),
                      na.rm = T)) %>%
    mutate("Polymers" = 
             rowMeans(cbind(data$`Tween 40`,
                            data$`Tween 80`,
                            data$`-Cyclodextrin`,
                            data$`Glycogen`),
                      na.rm = T)) %>%
    mutate("Carbohydrates" = 
             rowMeans(cbind(data$`D-Glucosaminic Acid`,
                            data$`-Methyl-D-Glucoside`,
                            data$`D-Xylose`,
                            data$`D-Galactonic Acid -Lactone`,
                            data$`i-Erythritol`,
                            data$`D-Mannitol`,
                            data$`N-Acetyl-D-Glucosamine`,
                            data$`D-Cellobiose`,
                            data$`Glucose-1-Phosphate`,
                            data$`D,L--Glycerol Phosphate`,
                            data$`-D-Lactose`),
                      na.rm = T)) %>%
    mutate("Phenols" = 
             rowMeans(cbind(data$`2-Hydroxy Benzoic Acid`,
                            data$`4-Hydroxy Benzoic Acid`),
                      na.rm = T))
}
# H144
G6_M1H144 <- Guilds6(M1H144)
G6_M6H144 <- Guilds6(M6H144)
G6_M12H144 <- Guilds6(M12H144)
G6_M18H144 <- Guilds6(M18H144)

Placed in a matrix

G6_To_matrix <- function(data){#dataframe to matrix
  data_t <-as.data.frame(paste(M1H72$Site, M1H72$Group))# combine the group and site variables
  data_tt <- bind_cols(as.data.frame(data_t), data) # create a new unique variable name
  
  colnames(data_tt)[colnames(data_tt)=="paste(M1H72$Site, M1H72$Group)"] <- "SitePlace" #give the new variable a name
  write.csv(data_tt, file = "G_TMdata.csv", row.names = FALSE)# create a csv file 
  TMdata <- read.csv("G_TMdata.csv", TRUE, sep = ",", row.names = 1, check.names = F)
  
  G_TMdata <- as.matrix(TMdata) # change the csv file to a data matrix
  return(G_TMdata)
}
# H144
G6_TM1H144 <- G6_To_matrix((G6_M1H144))
G6_TM6H144 <- G6_To_matrix((G6_M6H144))
G6_TM12H144 <- G6_To_matrix((G6_M12H144))
G6_TM18H144 <- G6_To_matrix((G6_M18H144))

Statistical testing between groups after 144 incubation hours was performed. Although statistical outliers were detected they were not removed from the analysis. Some samples did not have normal distributions and heteroscedasticity was observed between samples. Therefore, both the parametric (t.test) and non-parametric (wilcox.test) tests were performed.

### H144 ####
#### M1####

# M1 plot
G6_TM1H144.long <- arrange(data.frame(
  pivot_longer(cbind(M18H144[c(1:20),1:2]
                     ,G6_TM1H144[c(1:20),1:6])
               ,cols = c("Amines","Amino Acids", "Carbohydrates",
                         "Carboxylic Acids","Phenols",
                         "Polymers")
               ,names_to = "Guilds")),Guilds)
G6_TM1H144.long_rel <- G6_TM1H144.long$value-mean(G6_TM1H144.long$value)
G6_TM1H144.long <- bind_cols(G6_TM1H144.long,G6_TM1H144.long_rel)
New names:
colnames(G6_TM1H144.long) <- c("Site","Group","Guilds","value","relative_values")
write.csv(G6_TM1H144.long, file = "G6_TM1H144.long.csv", row.names = FALSE)
G6_TM1H144.long$Group <- factor(G6_TM1H144.long$Group
                                ,levels = c("control","beneath")
                                ,ordered = T)
Guilds_box_M1H144 <- ggplot(G6_TM1H144.long)+
  geom_boxplot(aes(fill = Group, y = relative_values, x = Guilds)
               ,outlier.colour = "black"
               ,outlier.size = .2)+
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("darkolivegreen","red4"))+
  #  ylim(-0.5,0.3)+
  theme+
  theme(legend.position = "none",axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, vjust = 1, hjust=1))+
  scale_x_discrete(label=NULL)+
  theme(plot.title=element_text(hjust=0.5))+
  labs(x = NULL, y = NULL, title = "One month")
Guilds_box_M1H144 <- Guilds_box_M1H144+
  geom_text(data=tibble(x=c(1), y=c(.7))
            ,aes(x=x, y=y, label="**"), size= 4
            ,inherit.aes = F)
Guilds_box_M1H144 <- Guilds_box_M1H144+
  geom_text(data=tibble(x=c(2), y=c(.7))
            ,aes(x=x, y=y, label="**"), size= 4
            ,inherit.aes = F)
Guilds_box_M1H144 <- Guilds_box_M1H144+
  geom_text(data=tibble(x=c(6), y=c(.7))
            ,aes(x=x, y=y, label="*"), size= 4
            ,inherit.aes = F)

# M6 plot
G6_TM6H144.long <- arrange(data.frame(
  pivot_longer(cbind(M18H144[c(1:20),1:2]
                     ,G6_TM6H144[c(1:20),1:6])
               ,cols = c("Amines","Amino Acids", "Carbohydrates",
                         "Carboxylic Acids","Phenols",
                         "Polymers")
               ,names_to = "Guilds")),Guilds)
G6_TM6H144.long_rel <- G6_TM6H144.long$value-mean(G6_TM6H144.long$value)
G6_TM6H144.long <- bind_cols(G6_TM6H144.long,G6_TM6H144.long_rel)
New names:
colnames(G6_TM6H144.long) <- c("Site","Group","Guilds","value","relative_values")
write.csv(G6_TM6H144.long, file = "G6_TM6H144.long.csv", row.names = FALSE)
G6_TM6H144.long$Group <- factor(G6_TM6H144.long$Group
                                ,levels = c("control","beneath")
                                ,ordered = T)
Guilds_box_M6H144 <- ggplot(G6_TM6H144.long)+
  geom_boxplot(aes(fill = Group, y = relative_values, x = Guilds)
               ,outlier.colour = "black"
               ,outlier.size = .2)+
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("darkolivegreen","red4"))+
 # ylim(-.8,1.3)+
  theme+
  theme(legend.position = "none",axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, vjust = 1, hjust=1))+
  scale_x_discrete(label=NULL)+
  theme(plot.title=element_text(hjust=0.5))+
  labs(#title = "M18H144", 
    x = NULL, y = NULL, title = "Six months")
Guilds_box_M6H144 <- Guilds_box_M6H144+
  geom_text(data=tibble(x=c(4), y=c(1.3))
            ,aes(x=x, y=y, label="**"), size= 4
            ,inherit.aes = F)

Alpha diversity Similar to the above, some samples did not have normal distributions and homoscedasticity so both parametric and non-parametric tests were performed.

## H144  ####
### Month 1 ####
H_controlM1H144 <- diversity((TM1H144)[1:10,1:31], index = "shannon")#Shannon index
H_beneathM1H144 <- diversity((TM1H144)[11:20,1:31], index = "shannon")#Shannon index
iD_controlM1H144 <- diversity((TM1H144)[1:10,1:31],"invsimpson")# inverse Simpson
iD_beneathM1H144 <- diversity((TM1H144)[11:20,1:31],"invsimpson")# inverse Simpson
No_controlM1H144 <- specnumber((TM1H144)[1:10,1:31]) 
No_beneathM1H144 <- specnumber((TM1H144)[11:20,1:31])  
JE_controlM1H144 <- H_controlM1H144/log(No_controlM1H144)# Pielous evenness
JE_beneathM1H144 <- H_beneathM1H144/log(No_beneathM1H144)# Pielous evenness

# Shannon entropy
hM1H144 <- bind_cols(H_controlM1H144,H_beneathM1H144)
New names:
HM1H144 <- data.frame(HM1H144=unlist(hM1H144,use.names = F))
# Simpsons
idM1H144 <- bind_cols(iD_controlM1H144,iD_beneathM1H144)
New names:
iDM1H144 <- data.frame(iDM1H144=unlist(idM1H144,use.names = F))
# Shannon evenness 
jeM1H144 <- bind_cols(JE_controlM1H144,JE_beneathM1H144)
New names:
JEM1H144 <- data.frame(JEM1H144=unlist(jeM1H144,use.names = F))

Grass_Env_Ctrl_Ben$Group <- factor(Grass_Env_Ctrl_Ben$Group
                                   ,levels = c("control","beneath")
                                   ,ordered=TRUE)# keep the levels order
Aplha_diversityM1H144 <- bind_cols(Group = Grass_Env_Ctrl_Ben,HM1H144
                                   ,iDM1H144,JEM1H144)
write.csv(Aplha_diversityM1H144,file = "Alpha_diversityM1H144.csv")

# Diversity index
H_controlM6H144 <- diversity((TM6H144)[1:10,1:31], index = "shannon")#Shannon index
H_beneathM6H144 <- diversity((TM6H144)[11:20,1:31], index = "shannon")#Shannon index
iD_controlM6H144 <- diversity((TM6H144)[1:10,1:31],"invsimpson")#inverse Simpson
iD_beneathM6H144 <- diversity((TM6H144)[11:20,1:31],"invsimpson")#inverse Simpson
No_controlM6H144 <- specnumber((TM6H144)[1:10,1:31]) 
No_beneathM6H144 <- specnumber((TM6H144)[11:20,1:31])  
JE_controlM6H144 <- H_controlM6H144/log(No_controlM6H144)#Pielous evenness
JE_beneathM6H144 <- H_beneathM6H144/log(No_beneathM6H144)#Pielous evenness
# Shannon entropy
hM6H144 <- bind_cols(H_controlM6H144,H_beneathM6H144)
New names:

# Simpsons

# Diversity index
H_controlM18H144 <- diversity((TM18H144)[1:10,1:31], index = "shannon")#Shannon index
H_beneathM18H144 <- diversity((TM18H144)[11:20,1:31], index = "shannon")#Shannon index
iD_controlM18H144 <- diversity((TM18H144)[1:10,1:31],"invsimpson")#inverse Simpson
iD_beneathM18H144 <- diversity((TM18H144)[11:20,1:31],"invsimpson")#inverse Simpson
No_controlM18H144 <- specnumber((TM18H144)[1:10,1:31]) 
No_beneathM18H144 <- specnumber((TM18H144)[11:20,1:31])  
JE_controlM18H144 <- H_controlM18H144/log(No_controlM18H144)#Pielous evenness
JE_beneathM18H144 <- H_beneathM18H144/log(No_beneathM18H144)#Pielous evenness
# Shannon entropy
hM18H144 <- bind_cols(H_controlM18H144,H_beneathM18H144)

#Simpsons Reciprocal - Community function####
InvsimpsonsMonths <- cbind(Aplha_diversityM1H144[1:2],iDM1H144,iDM6H144,iDM12H144,iDM18H144)
colnames(InvsimpsonsMonths) <- c("site", "Group","1","6","12","18")
InvsimpsonsMonths <- InvsimpsonsMonths %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = c("1","6","12","18"), 
               names_to = "Month", values_to = "Value")
InvsimpsonsMonths <-data.frame(InvsimpsonsMonths)

InvsimpsonsMonths$Month <- factor(InvsimpsonsMonths$Month,
                                  levels = c("1","6","12","18"),ordered = T)
InvsimpsonsMonths$Group <- factor(InvsimpsonsMonths$Group,
                                  levels = c("beneath","control"),ordered = T)

Alpha.plot_PS_Div <- 
  ggplot(InvsimpsonsMonths,aes(x=Month, 
                               y=Value,
                               fill = Group))+
  geom_boxplot()+
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("red2" ,"green3"))+
  theme+
  theme(axis.title.y = element_blank())+

Beta diversity (dissimilarity) Significance was also confirmed with permanova and anosim. Anosim results can be defined as: #0.75 < R < 1 - highly different #0.5 < R < 0.75 - different #0.25 < R < 0.5- different with some overlap #0.1 < R < 0.25 similar with some differences (or high overlap) #R < 0.1 - similar

chem_env.long <- pivot_longer(chem_env,cols = c("NO3","NH4","P","SO4"), names_to = "Nutrient")

chem_env.long$samples <- factor(chem_env.long$samples
                                ,levels = c("M1 Ctrl","M1 Bnth",
                                            "M6 Ctrl","M6 Bnth",
                                            "M12 Ctrl","M12 Bnth",
                                            "M18 Ctrl","M18 Bnth")
                                ,ordered = T)
chem_env.long$samples <- factor(chem_env.long$samples
                                ,levels = c("M1 Ctrl","M1 Bnth",
                                            "M6 Ctrl","M6 Bnth",
                                            "M12 Ctrl","M12 Bnth",
                                            "M18 Ctrl","M18 Bnth")
                                ,ordered = T)
chem_env.long$month <- factor(chem_env.long$month
                              ,levels = c("M1 control","M1 beneath",
                                          "M6 control","M6 beneath",
                                          "M12 control","M12 beneath",
                                          "M18 control","M18 beneath")
                              ,ordered = T)


ggplot(chem_env.long, aes(x = samples, y = value, fill = Nutrient)) +
  geom_bar(stat = 'identity') +
  facet_wrap(~Nutrient, ncol = 2) +
  theme+
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))+
  labs(x = 'Group', y = 'ppm', title = 'Measured Nutrient') +

  scale_fill_manual('Nutrient', values = c( 'red','coral2', 'steelblue', 'pink'))

Sole-carbon substrate utilisation#### SIMPER result indicate sole-carbon substrate contribution to dissimilarity and also give an indication of the differences in substrate utilisation between the beneath and control groups at the different time points.

SimperSummary_M12H144

SimperSummary_M18H144

To compare the the mean substrate utilisation between the beneath and control directly the normality and homoscedasticity was analised after which the difference in mean were compared with t-tests and its non-parametric equivalent. If the variance was not equal (levenes.test) the t.test was adjusted to var.equal = F For the non-parametric test, both the paired (Wilcoxon Signed-Rank Test) and non-pared (Mann-Whitney U Test) versions were performed. # M1

#Pyruvic Acid Methyl Ester
shapiro.test(TM1H144[1:10,1])#normality of the control group

    Shapiro-Wilk normality test

In the below analysis (Tween 80), beneath samples were not normally distributed. It was also considered that there are only 10 replicates whereas >15 would be ideal, not reducing statistical power. In the below data there were also instances of heteroscedasticity. Thus, it was decided to use non-parametric statistical testing.

In some of the leveneTest results theres are tied values. When tied values exist, the exact p-values might be challenging to compute, leading to approximate results. In practice, tied values are common and often unavoidable. As long as youre aware of them and interpret results cautiously, they shouldnt pose a significant problem.
